1. e4 d5 { The Scandinavian is a more popular opening at lower levels, seen in 11% of the games at the sub-1600 level (versus just 2% of the time at master level). Which means we should spend some time on it and make sure we're ready for the arising positions, which see a somewhat earlier confrontation than the other lines Black can play. } 2. exd5 { We should take the pawn to lure Black's queen into the open where we can attack it. } 2... Qxd5 { The predominant move. } (2... Nf6 { is seen occasionally (13% of sub-1600 games). We can gain a pleasant advantage by rather simple means: } 3. d4 Nxd5 4. Nf3 { and even knowing a simple setup like Be2/0-0/c4/Nc3 will suffice for an edge. But in certain cases we can also be more ambitious: } { [%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Gc2c4,Gb1c3] } 4... Nc6 { The most common below 1600, with } (4... Bg4 { in a close 2nd place. }) 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 { As tempting as it is to kick the knight immediately, I realized that it pays to be patient here: } 6... Bg4 { Black puts a lot of pressure on our d4 pawn, but we have an effective counter: } { [%csl Gd4] } 7. d5 Ne5 8. Be2 { This breaking of the pin also sets a neat tactical trick. } 8... Bxf3 9. Bxf3 { In most games below 1600, Black falls for it: } 9... Nxc4 { Even without this blunder, White was already much better with the space, better development and bishop pair. } 10. Qa4+ { Loose Pieces Drop Off! We win the undefended knight with this fork. } { [%csl Gc4][%cal Ga4c4,Ga4e8] }) 3. Nc3 { It pays to kick their queen, developing with tempo to seize an early initiative. } 3... Qd8 { Seen in 35% of the games below 1600, although I faced it proportionally even more often in my own games. This retreat keeps the queen safe, but does give up the initiative to White. } (3... Qa5 { This is the main line at master level. Now the Leonhardt Gambit with } 4. b4 { scores extremely well for White (57% win rate!) and I'm happy to recommend it, as Black usually meets it quite badly. } 4... Qxb4 5. Rb1 Qd6 6. Nf3 { We have a nice lead in development with our rook on the half-open b-file, and Black usually misplays it over the next few moves. } 6... Nf6 (6... Bg4 { is nearly as common as 6...Nf6, but of course } 7. Rxb7 { regains the pawn with a huge initiative. } { [%csl Gc7][%cal Gc3b5] }) 7. d4 { Even if Black plays a correct defence like 7...e6 or 7...g6, White still has full compensation for the pawn. But usually in sub-1600 games Black played } 7... Bg4 { (38% of games!), allowing } 8. Rxb7 { with a clear advantage now that the pawn is regained. }) (3... Qe6+ { is a check that's not very good, but can be a little tricky if you haven't seen it before. } 4. Be2 Qg6 { Threatening the g2-pawn. Black gets a reasonable game if we defend it, but we can sacrifice it instead for a massive initiative. } { [%csl Gg2] } 5. Nf3 { A great move, not fearing what will be the 4th move of Black's queen. } 5... Qxg2 6. Rg1 Qh3 7. d4 { While Black has only moved their queen around the whole game, White has swiftly developed their forces. The lead in development is amplified by the open position, and White is actually winning with best play from here. } { [%cal Gc1f4,Ge1c1,Gd1d2] }) (3... Qe5+ { This queen check looks ridiculous, but it's a favourite of GM Shimanov online. } 4. Be2 Bg4 { Black wants to recycle their bishop as trading minor pieces usually helps the side with less space relieve their cramp. } 5. d4 Bxe2 6. Ngxe2 Qa5 { If Black gets time to consolidate with moves like ...Nf6, ...e6, ...Nc6 and ...0-0-0, they will have a solid foundation with some counterattacking potential to boot. So I suggest disrupting Black's setup as soon as possible: } 7. b4 { You might notice the similarity here to our Leonhardt Gambit vs. 3...Qa5, but here it works a lot better again. } 7... Qxb4 { Taking the pawn is not a good idea, but it demonstrates our idea clearly. } 8. Qd3 { This is even better than immediately regaining the pawn with Rb1, as it avoids the ...Qc4 defence. } 8... Nc6 9. Rb1 Qd6 { White is winning in more than one way here. } 10. d5 { The engine's favourite, playing for the initiative, but the simple } (10. Rxb7 { is also decisive - Black's king is simply too weak here. } { [%csl Ge8][%cal Gc3b5] })) 4. d4 { White occupies the centre with their remaining pawn. } 4... Nf6 (4... e6 5. Nf3 Nf6 { just transposes to our main line. }) 5. Nf3 e6 { The most common move, seen in 1/3rd of the games (and it would be even more if you included the 4...e6 5.Nf3 Nf6 move order). It's not as bad a system as it looks, though it is rather passive, and my suggested setup exploits this. } (5... Nc6 { is the 2nd most common move, but } 6. Bb5 { is a rather annoying pin that gives us control of the game, as Black has no good pawn break to challenge our d4-pawn. } { [%cal Ge1g1,Gb5e8] }) (5... Bg4 { is the usual move at master level, and recommended in an old Scandinavian course by IM Bartholomew. A good reply is } 6. h3 Bxf3 (6... Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 { gives White too much initiative against the vulnerable g6-bishop. } { [%cal Gf1g2,Gh3h5] }) 7. Qxf3 { We can play this because of the attack on b7. } { [%cal Gf3b7] } 7... c6 8. Be3 { We defend our pawn and develop. } (8. g4 { scores the best of all, but it's a bit computerish and impractical for a beginners repertoire. }) 8... e6 { With our centre secured, I suggest switching to castling short: } 9. Bd3 Bb4 10. O-O { It transpires that the doubled pawns are no problem for us: } 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 { We can use the doubled pawns dynamically with c4, and we have nice half-open files for our rooks after Rab1 and Rfe1 to go with our bishop pair, space and development. } { [%cal Gc3c4,Gf1e1,Ga1b1] }) 6. Bd3 { I've recently switched to this move in my online games and have been pretty happy with the resulting positions. } (6. Bg5 Be7 7. Bd3 { is an equally valid move order that transposes to our main line (6.Bd3 Be7 7.Bg5), and can be recommended if you want to discourage ...Bb4 (personally, I want to encourage it). }) 6... Be7 { This is seen in 30% of the games, preparing castling. } (6... Bb4 { is just as common and can be met in various ways. But it's good to know that we don't need to fear ...Bxc3: } 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O { It's hard for Black to really get at our doubled pawns (...Nd5 is well met by c4), whereas our attack on their king comes naturally: } 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. Re1 { and a subsequent rook lift along the third rank, backed up by our bishops, will exert inexorable pressure on Black's king. } { [%cal Ge1e3,Ge3h3,Ge3g3,Gc1a3,Gc1g5] }) 7. Bg5 { A small twist - while there's nothing wrong with castling short, I like castling long for a more dynamic middlegame where the price of a mistake is much higher for Black. } 7... O-O { Black castles short, but not necessarily to safety in the long-term :) } 8. Qd2 { I love this queen move, preparing long castling and also giving us some fun ideas of sacking on h6 if they play ...h6 later. } 8... Nbd7 { The most common, but a little passive. } (8... h6 9. Bxh6 gxh6 10. Qxh6 { is already a crushing attack for White. Black is unable to bring pieces to the defence properly. } { [%csl Gg8][%cal Ge1c1,Gg2g5,Gf3g5] }) 9. O-O-O b6 10. h4 { It's natural to charge the h-pawn when we want to attack Black's king from a less open position. } 10... Bb7 { White has a lot of moves here that give a big advantage, but I'll go with a tricky one that anticipates their most natural move. } 11. Qe2 (11. h5 { is the most common and also not bad. If } 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 { we get the half-open g-file for our attack on their king. } { [%cal Gh1g1,Gg1g8] }) 11... c5 { When facing ...c5 in the middlegame in bullet, I often wasn't quite sure of the best way to deal with it. But with our rook opposite their queen, the answer becomes easy. } { [%cal Gd1d8] } 12. dxc5 { We remove the obstacles to the d8-queen! } 12... Bxc5 (12... Nxc5 { loses the queen to } 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Rxd8) 13. Ne5 { Black has a tough time dealing with all our piece pressure. We don't really care if they later grab the g2-pawn as it just opens the g-file for the attack to their king. } { [%csl Gg1,Gg2][%cal Gd3h7,Gd1d8] } *


