1. e4 { I have grouped the 1...d6 and 1...g6 systems together because they are often similar in spirit with the overall dark-squared strategy, and also neither move is popular enough on its own to deserve a full separate game. } 1... d6 { This, the Pirc Defence, is seen in just 3% of games, but this move can trip some inexperienced players up as Black doesn't give White a clear target to attack early. } (1... g6 { The Modern Defense, also seen in 3% of games below 1600. It's quite flexible (and I played it a lot over the years) but can be exploited by a savvy White player. } 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 { First we take over the centre and ensure our e4-pawn is protected, neutralizing early counterattacks like ...c5 or ...d5. } 3... d6 { The most common, seen in 35% of sub-1600 games but it's a lot more popular at master level. } (3... e6 { tries to play either a Hippo setup with Bb7/Nd7/Ne7/Bg7 or a more aggressive ...d5 counterattack later. Against such passive setups, I suggest charging the h-pawn forward: } { [%cal Gg8e7,Gd7d5,Gd7d6] } 4. h4 Ne7 5. h5 { and we can either open up the h-file for a kingside attack with hxg6, or mess up their setup with h6, depending on how they play it. It may surprise you to learn that White is already close to winning once the pawn gets to h5. }) 4. Be3 { I really like this setup of Be3/Qd2/0-0-0, as it's easy to remember (develop all the queenside pieces first) and also punishes Black for their most natural reply, which is castling short ASAP to 'complete' their king's fianchetto setup. } 4... Nd7 { If Black delays ...Ngf6, we can still play our usual setup of developing the queenside first. } (4... Nf6 { is seen most of the time, but it transposes directly to our Pirc coverage (via. 1...d6 2.d4 Nf6 3.Nc3 g6 4.Be3 Bg7). }) (4... Nc6 { If they play a funny move like this, just continue normally: } 5. Qd2 Nf6 6. f3 { This is the one adjustment - if ...Ng4 is a threat, stop it with f3. This also supports a later g4 to build up our kingside pawn storm against their king. }) 5. Qd2 { We set up the queen and bishop battery so that Ngf6 is well met by Bh6. } { [%cal Gg8f6,Ge3h6] } 5... e5 6. O-O-O { We can even ignore the central tension for now and play our usual setup. } 6... exd4 7. Bxd4 Ngf6 8. f3 { Even though we don't have an easy Bh6, we can charge our kingside pawns toward their king once they castle short for a very strong attack. } { [%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h5] }) 2. d4 { When Black plays the opening passively, we should occupy the centre immediately. } 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 { Now Black has a choice, although most of the time (61% at sub-1600 level) they go for the kingside fianchetto. } 3... g6 { This is the position most people think of when you say 'Pirc Defence'. But if you looked at our answer to 1...g6 already, you'll know what's coming. } (3... c6 { is the Pribyl or Czech Defence, seen in 14% of games. But it's not very good - after an ambitious setup like } 4. f4 Qa5 { Threatening to win our e4-pawn with the pin, which explains our next move. } { [%cal Gf6e4,Ga5e1] } 5. Bd3 e5 6. Nf3 { , we have a strong grip over the centre and the queen is a bit strangely placed on a5. } { [%cal Gc1e3,Ge1g1] }) 4. Be3 { White's best scoring move with 54.5% at the sub-1600 level. It's only seen 5% of the time there but is virtually the main line at the master level, because our plan of Qd2/0-0-0/Bh6/h4-h5 (often with f3 thrown in at some point) is so easy to understand and execute. } 4... Bg7 { Developing the bishop naturally. } (4... c6 { is the main line at the master level, to avoid the plan I'm about to show, but almost no one plays like this below 2000. }) 5. Qd2 { We prepare long castling then Bh6 to trade their strong bishop and start a kingside attack. } 5... O-O { The predominant move (60% of games below 1600), but already a bit of a mistake, as it castles into White's coming attack. } (5... Ng4 { is an empty shot after } 6. Bg5 { - it's important to keep our dark-squared bishop alive for the attack on Black's king. }) 6. O-O-O { We may not necessarily play Bh6 on the very next move, but after f3 it very much comes on the agenda. } 6... Nc6 { The most common move (17% of games below 1600), but we can meet it quite comfottably. } (6... Nbd7 { is nearly as common, but can be met in the standard way with } 7. f3 { followed by Bh6 and h4-h5 with an easy h-file attack on Black's king, while Black has not even begun their counterplay. } { [%cal Ge3h6,Gh2h5] }) (6... c6 { is only seen 8% of the time below 1600, but is the most common at master play. A good reply is } 7. f3 b5 8. Bh6 { , when our e4-pawn is guarded against ...b4/...Nxe4 and we are ready to attack their king with h4-h5, forcing open the h-file one way or another. }) 7. f3 { We play this to avoid ...Ng4 and also because } (7. d5 Ne5 { gives Black counterplay with the active knight in the centre. } { [%cal Gc7c5] }) 7... e5 { The usual move, but now d5 gains in strength. } 8. d5 (8. Nge2 { is also good if you want a more open position with } 8... exd4 9. Nxd4 { [%cal Gg2g5,Gh2h5] }) 8... Ne7 9. g4 { White's attack plays itself from here. Note that the attempt to counterattack with } { [%cal Gh2h5,Gc1b1] } 9... c6 { fails tactically to } 10. dxc6 Nxc6 11. Qxd6 { , winning a pawn. } (11. h4 { is even stronger to the engine, but it's hard to argue against taking a free pawn. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] }) *


