1. e4 { This final chapter may seem longer than usual, but that's because I bunched five sidelines together rather than separating them into individual chapters. None of these moves are seen in more than 2% of games total so I wouldn't worry too much about remembering every little detail. } 1... Nf6 { The Alekhine Defence, which is one of the trickier sidelines due to the early attack on our centre, but objectively not that great. } (1... b6 { The Owen's Defence has a rather passive reputation and you'll notice that a lot of these sidelines can be met in a rather systematic way. } 2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 { I like to defend the pawn with the bishop, to avoid potential pins after Nc3 e6 and ...Bb4. It also scores a nice 54% for White below 1600. } 3... e6 { The most common move, continuing with the light-squared strategy. } (3... g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 { tries to play in a Hippo style with the Double Fianchetto. But you may already recall how to deal with the Hippo: } 5. h4 { forces some early weaknesses in Black's setup, before they can complete it. } { [%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6] }) (3... Nf6 4. Qe2 { transposes to 3...e6 after } 4... e6 5. Nf3 { . }) 4. Nf3 { We prepare to castle short. This setup with e4/d4/Bd3/Nf3/0-0/c3 is known as the "Geller Setup' and it's an easy way to meet most of Black's sidelines. } 4... Nf6 { Attacking our centre. } 5. Qe2 { The practical move, continuing the Geller Setup with 0-0, c3 and Nbd2 in some order. White is clearly better due to the space advantage. } (5. e5 { is even more annoying for Black, although they can avoid it with the 3...Nf6 move order. } 5... Nd5 6. c4 Nb4 7. Be2 { Black's knight is very out of play and will soon be driven back with a3. } { [%cal Ga2a3] })) (1... Nc6 { The Nimzowitsch Defence, which is a better system than its unpopularity would suggest. But we can still get an advantage with logical moves. } 2. d4 { We should take the centre, as } (2. Nf3 e5 { move orders us out of the King's Gambit. } { [%cal Gf2f4] }) 2... e5 { Played in 28% of games, but we can thwart Black's attempts to transpose to 1.e4 e5 by taking more central space. } (2... d5 { This is the best move for Black (and seen in 27% of games), trying to get a good version of a Scandinavian after the exchange of the e4- and d5-pawns. So we should avoid that: } 3. e5 { I haven't recommended closed structures a lot in this repertoire, but here it makes perfect sense because the usual counterplay against our centre with ...c5 is blocked by their knight on c6. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gc7c5] } 3... Bf5 { Unlike in the French, Black develops their bishop more actively, but it's not enough to solve their problems. } { [%csl Gc8,Ge6][%cal Gc6b4,Gb4c2] } 4. c3 { A practical move to prevent annoying ...Nb4 attacks. } 4... e6 (4... f6 { If they attack our centre, we can shore it up with } 5. f4 { for a solid pawn chain. }) 5. f4 { Objectively speaking, this is not the best move for White, but it scores the best for White, and has the advantage that our next several moves become very easy to play and understand when we already have the strong pawn chain b2-c3-d4-e5-f4 to guard us against any dangers. } 5... Be7 { Black continues developing their kingside. } 6. Nf3 Nh6 7. Bd3 { We are ready to castle, with a tiny advantage due to our space advantage and the fact ...f6 is neutralized by our f4-pawn. } (7. Be2 { is objectively a little bit better, pointing out that the f5-bishop can potentially become a target later. } { [%csl Gf5][%cal Ge1g1] })) 3. d5 { Kicking their knight with tempo. } 3... Nce7 { The best square for the knight, preparing to go to g6. } { [%cal Ge7g6] } (3... Nd4 4. c3 { traps their knight and is a common blunder below 1600. }) 4. Nf3 { We attack their e5-pawn immediately to reduce their options. } 4... d6 { The most common in practice, but the easier move to handle in my view. } (4... Ng6 { When their knight goes to g6, it's natural to try and kick it away: } 5. h4 h5 6. Bg5 { and Black must make some sort of concession. } 6... f6 7. Be3 { Black is no longer able to play ...Nh6 or develop their f8-bishop actively (as ...Bb4 is met by c3) and greatly suffers as a result. }) 5. c4 { Now we can play an improved King's Indian where the knight is a bit misplaced on e7 and we can hold back their ...f5 counterplay with h3 and a well-timed g4. I realize it may not be the most natural habitat for a 1.e4 player to play a 1.d4 structure, but it's a massively improved version for us. } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gh2h3,Gf1d3] }) (1... a6 { The St. George Defense, which engines say is not that terrible, but only if Black transposes to a weaker version of another opening right after. } 2. d4 { We take the centre, as usual. } 2... b5 { Preparing ...Bb7 to attack our centre, but you'll notice it takes a move longer for Black compared to the Owen's Defence (1...b6/2...Bb7). } 3. Bd3 { We defend our pawn in anticipation of ...Bb7. } 3... Bb7 4. Nf3 { While it's not the top engine line, sticking with the Geller Setup is practical, easy for us for remember, and still keeps a very nice advantage. } 4... e6 5. c3 c5 6. O-O { Our subsequent moves from here can be Re1 and Nbd2 to overprotect the e4-pawn. } 6... c4 { A little bit of a strategic error, releasing the tension against our centre. But it's the most common by far below 1600. } 7. Bc2 Nf6 8. Re1 { We can continue with our normal setup for a big advantage, playing e5 at the right time to increase our space advantage. } (8. e5 Nd5 9. Ng5 { immediately is also tempting, going for the kill with Qh5, Qf3 or f4-f5 depending on how they play it. } { [%csl Gf7][%cal Gf2f5] })) (1... f5 { is the Duras Gambit and the worst move on the board for Black. It's very easy to deal with: just take the pawn and hang on to it. } 2. exf5 { We already threaten Qh5 to win more material. } { [%cal Gd1h5] } 2... Nf6 3. d4 d5 4. Bd3 { White is up a pawn with the much better position to boot. } { [%cal Gd3f5] }) 2. e5 { We attack their knight for an early initiative. } 2... Nd5 3. d4 { Establishing the dream centre, only a bit further advanced this time. } { [%csl Gd4,Ge5] } 3... d6 { Black wants to attack our centre with pawns and pieces, but we can support it with our own pieces. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd6e5] } (3... e6 { is seen in nearly a quarter of games (23%) below 1600. But it's very passive and after } 4. c4 { we have total central domination basically for free. } { [%cal Gb1c3,Gg1f3] }) 4. Nf3 { I like this move, overprotecting e5 and allowing us to activate our knight if they exchange. } 4... dxe5 { Seen in 35% of games below 1600, this is also popular at master level, to reduce White's space advantage. } (4... Bg4 { is historically the most common move at master level, but has a poor reputation nowadays. It's still seen 27% of the time below 1600 though as the pin on the knight is rather natural. } 5. Be2 { We break the pin and prepare short castling. } 5... Nc6 6. O-O { We complete kingside development, as Black is still not threatening to win our e5-pawn. } (6. c4 Nb6 7. e6 fxe6 8. O-O { is a really fun gambit I discovered while preparing this Study, but it's not an appropriate suggestion for less advanced players. }) 6... dxe5 { Trying to leave White with an e5-pawn to target. } (6... Bxf3 7. Bxf3 dxe5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Bxd5 { demonstrates the previous point. }) 7. Nxe5 { This recapture with the knight thwarts Black's plans. } 7... Bxe2 8. Qxe2 Nxd4 { Black grabs the pawn as otherwise their position is pretty depressing without any space. } 9. Qc4 { The key move, hitting their knight and preparing Rd1. } 9... Ne6 10. Rd1 c6 11. Nc3 { White already has a decisive attack for the pawn due to Black's lack of development. } { [%cal Gc4f7,Gd1d8] }) (4... Nc6 { can be a bit tricky the first time one sees it. But a good reply is } 5. c4 (5. Bb5 { is a practical alternative if you don't want to sack a pawn out of the opening. }) 5... Nb6 6. e6 { and Black has a hard time getting their pieces out after this pawn sacrifice. } 6... Bxe6 { Surprisingly this is the most common move below 1600, even though it just loses a piece after } (6... fxe6 { is correct, when after } 7. Nc3 { White is significantly better, based on meeting ...g6 with h4-h5 and ...e5 with d5. In either case, Black struggles to develop their kingside properly. } { [%csl Ge7,Ge6] }) 7. d5 { . }) 5. Nxe5 { We recapture with the knight, both to avoid giving Black a target in the e5-pawn, and to set up some interesting tactical ideas against f7. It's good news for us that Black's most common moves below 1600 all have some problems. } 5... f6 { I was stunned to see this was the most common below 1600 (19% of games) as it's a clear blunder. } (5... e6 { doesn't look entirely stupid despite blocking in the c8-bishop, but } 6. Qf3 { forces some concession from Black to defend the f7-pawn, and we have a strong initiative in the arising position. } { [%cal Gf3f7,Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Ge1c1] }) (5... Nc6 { is a bit of a strategic mistake, but the greatest punishment comes from } 6. Bb5 { , pinning the knight. }) (5... Bf5 { also runs into problems on f7 after } 6. Qf3 e6 7. Bd3 { , when Black must contort to avoid a Qxf7 mate. }) (5... Nd7 { is only played in 10% of the games, but I included it because the refutation is a bit complicated: } 6. Nxf7 Kxf7 7. Qh5+ { In most games Black doesn't even try to save the knight with ...Ke6, making our life very easy. } 7... g6 (7... Ke6 8. c4 { These lines are admittedly way too complicated to cover in a Study for sub-1600 players, but you can trust me that White is much better with Black's king stuck in the centre. It's like a Fried Liver Attack for White, only better. } { [%cal Gd4d5] }) 8. Qxd5+ { White is up a pawn with a big attack on Black's uncastled king. }) 6. Qh5+ { This just wins material by force. } 6... g6 7. Nxg6 hxg6 8. Qxh8 { White is up an exchange and a pawn, easily enough to win. } *


