1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e5 { We attack their knight with tempo. } (4. Nc3 { This move is honestly not bad, but I've recommended a more aggressive reply as } 4... d5! { gives Black an improved version of the ...d5 lines. Still, this was only played in 11% of games below 1600 so your move (followed by d4 and Bxf4) would probably still work in practice. }) (4. d3 { This is a bit passive - we'd rather play d4 if we can help it. }) 4... Nd5 5. Nc3 (5. d4 { This is natural but runs into 5...d6 when the weakness of e3 will lead to some problems for White down the stretch. My suggested variation avoids that issue. } 5... d6 { [%cal Gd5e3] }) (5. Bc4 { Not the worst idea in the world, but we lose the initiative after 5...Nb6 (hitting our bishop) and ...d6. } 5... Nb6 6. Bb3 d6) 5... Nxc3 6. dxc3 (6. bxc3 { In most positions we should recapture toward the centre, but here it's more important to get in Bxf4 ASAP }) 6... Nc6 7. Bxf4 { We have a strong initiative after Qd2/0-0-0 with our lead in development and central space advantage. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] } *


