1. e4 e5 2. f4 d6 { This move is a bit passive, but not entirely ridiculous. } 3. Nf3 (3. fxe5 { This is a blunder because of the ...Qh4 fork - please don't fall for this! We can avoid it easily enough by starting with 3.Nf3 }) (3. d3!? { This is a pretty good move in fact, not letting Black play a later ...exf4 to transpose back into the King's Gambit Accepted. Now play 3.Nf3 to continue with the exercise } { [%cal Gg1f3,Gf1e2,Ge1g1] }) 3... Nc6 { White has many good options here, but try going for the most schematic one. } 4. Bc4 (4. Bb5 { This move scores well in practice, but I find 4...exf4! a bit annoying - here our bishop would rather be on c4 to target f7 } 4... exf4) (4. fxe5 { This is not such a bad alternative - now play 4.Bc4 }) (4. Nc3 { This move order is equally valid - now play 4.Bc4 }) (4. d3 { This is quite a safe alternative, now play 4.Bc4 }) 4... Nf6 { Attacking our e4-pawn! This is a new move that I've included in this Exercise to help you remember the Vienna setup for when Black plays more passively. } 5. d3 { We defend our pawn with the secure c2-d3-e4 pawn chain. } (5. Nc3 { This is almost as good as my suggestion, but I find the 'Fork Trick' with 5...Nxe4 6.Nxe4 d5 to be an annoying extra option that I'd rather avoid } 5... Nxe4 6. Nxe4 d5) (5. O-O { Defend your c3-pawn first } { [%cal Gf6e4] }) 5... Be7 6. O-O (6. fxe5 { This is a good alternative, now try 6.0-0 }) (6. Nc3 { This is a good alternative, now try 6.0-0 }) 6... O-O 7. Nc3 { We have stabilized the centre and are ready to play moves like f5 to start a kingside attack. We can also play a3/a4 at some stage so that ...Na5 doesn't trade off our strong Italian bishop after Ba2. } { [%cal Gf4f5,Ga2a4] } (7. fxe5 { This is a good alternative, now try 6.0-0 }) 7... Bg4 { A final bonus exercise - how to deal with the pin? } 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 { We have the bishop pair advantage and the makings of a strong long-term attack against Black's king, thanks to our central space and unopposed light-squared bishop. } { [%csl Gc4,Ge4,Gf4][%cal Gc4g8] } *


