1. e4 e5 2. f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 { The main line at the master level, so it makes sense to cover it in an exercise. } 4. h4 { We should undermine their kingside pawn structure as soon as possible. } (4. d4 { This move gives Black time to consolidate their structure with ...d6/...Bg7/...h6 or even go on the offensive with ...g4/...Qh4. Look for a more aggressive move on the kingside }) (4. Bc4 { This move gives Black time to consolidate their structure with ...Nc6/...d6/...Bg7/...h6 or even go on the offensive with ...g4/...Qh4. Look for a more aggressive move on the kingside }) (4. Nc3 { This move gives Black time to consolidate their structure with ...d6/...Bg7/...h6 or even go on the offensive with ...g4/...Qh4. Look for a more aggressive move on the kingside }) 4... g4 5. Ne5 (5. Ng5 { This Allgaier Gambit is unfortunately not sound as 5...h6 traps our knight and we don't get enough of an attack in return }) 5... d6 6. Nxg4 Nf6 { This is a new move for us but it's very popular at the master level, so I included it as an Exercise. } 7. Nxf6+ { We are best off exchanging to buy time to develop our other pieces. } (7. Nf2 { This is too passive, Black gets a strong kingside initiative with ...Rg8 and ...Bh6 after which our kingside is just a bit too weak. }) 7... Qxf6 8. Nc3 { The position offers chances for both sides, we can play moves like d4, Qf3 or Nd5 next depending on what they go for. Both sides have weaknesses but it's an interesting game where the better player will win. } (8. d4 { This is also fine, now play 8.Nc3. }) *


