1. e4 e6 { The French, which can be a bit tricky for players who aren't comfortable in closed positions. Fortunately for us, my recommendation leads to mostly open positions } 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 (3. Nc3 { This is the main line in master play, but I'm recommending the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 in this repertoire, to avoid a 3.Nc3 Bb4 pin }) (3. e5 { This is a reasonable alternative, but I'm recommending the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 in this repertoire, to avoid a 3.Nc3 Bb4 pin }) (3. exd5 { This is a safe alternative, but I'm recommending the Tarrasch with 3.Nd2 in this repertoire, to avoid a 3.Nc3 Bb4 pin }) 3... dxe4 { The Rubinstein Variation, which is a bit passive but not entirely bad } 4. Nxe4 { We regain the pawn and have a central space advantage. } 4... Nf6 { How should we deal with the offer to trade knights? } 5. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { The queen looks a bit exposed on f6, but let's develop naturally and take it from there. } 6. Nf3 (6. Bd3 { This is a good alternative, now start with 6.Nf3 }) 6... Bd6 { This is a new move for us, but we can meet it in the same way as usual. } 7. Bd3 { A seemingly innocent bishop development... } (7. Bg5 { This is a good alternative and even marginally more precise to the engine. But I've recommended 7.Bd3 because Black handles it worse in practice }) 7... O-O { A big mistake, but Black's position was already difficult. } 8. Bg5 *


